stimulus: Welcome to the experiment. Press any key to begin.

This experiment uses your camera for eye tracking.

No video is saved from this experiment. The only data recorded are predictions about where you are looking.

Before we begin, there are a few things to do that can improve the accuracy of the eye tracking.

If you wear glasses and can complete the task without them, please remove your glasses.

If you need to keep your glasses on to read this text, you can leave them on.

Please close additional browser tabs and apps running in the background.

The eye tracker works best when there are fewer things running at the same time.

Try to avoid bright lights behind you.

The eye tracker works best if your face is well lit from the front.

If you can, adjust the lighting in your room.
Turn off anything that may produce an alert or notification during the task.

On the next screen, you will check to see if your webcam is working.

We will calibrate the eye tracker later on in the experiment.

This experiment also uses audio prompts.

Let's have a quick audio check.

Follow the instructions in the audio prompt to continue.

The audio prompt will loop until the instruction is followed.

For the following experiment, you will observe a grid of images split into four themed quadrants.

For example, a quadrant filled with related images might look like this.
Your task is to remember where each object is located as well as which way the object is facing.
You may not use any tools (including your phone or a piece of paper) to help you remember how they are arranged.

After you have tried your best to memorize the grid of images, you will hear a series of statements.

Those statements will be about the way an item is facing or how an item is positioned relative to other items.

For example, you may hear, "The house is facing to the right," or "The house is to the left of the school."

You will indicate whether you think these statements are true or false.

It’s time for you to get familiar with the objects.

You will see four lists of objects.

After each list, you will see images of these objects displayed in one quadrant of the screen.

You will be asked to confirm which way each object is facing, which you can answer by pressing either the left or right arrow keys.

Once all four quadrants have been presented to you individually, all of the objects will be presented on the screen at once.

You will then have an additional 60 seconds to continue studying their placement.

You have an additional 60 seconds to study the items.

Try your best to remember where each item is and how it is positioned.

Next, you'll see a series of dots appear on the screen. Look at each dot and click on it.

Because this is meant to calibrate the eye tracker, please move only your eyes and not your head as you do so.

Now we'll measure the accuracy of the calibration.

Keep your head still, and move your eyes to look at the dots.

You do not need to click on the dots this time.

The accuracy of the calibration is a little lower than we'd like.

Let's try calibrating one more time.

Keep your head still, look at the dots, and click on them.

Now we'll measure the accuracy of the calibration.

Keep your head still, and move your eyes to look at the dots.

You do not need to click on the dots this time.

Great, we're done with calibration!

Remember to keep your head still as you continue to the experiment.

Next, you will hear statements about the objects you just viewed.

Please indicate whether those statements are true or false.

On your keyboard, press “t” for “true” and “f” for “false”.

Please rest your left index finger on the ‘f’ key and your right index finger on the ‘t’ key and leave them there while you respond to the statements.

Keep your eyes on the cross in the center of the screen for the entirety of this section.

You are encouraged to answer as quickly as possible without guessing.
